\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Wow. That was\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 a thing. An evolved skill, one upgraded title and three new titles, all from solving one problem he only found because the System decided to crank up the difficulty of his evaluation. Not that he was going to argue, it felt damn good. Apparently he had a natural talent for controlling mana, who\u8217\'92d have thunk it? He also had to admit that seeing concrete evidence for how good he was at something and how those skills improved was a hell of a motivator. It felt awesome watching the numbers go up.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Of course, the experience was revealing in a bunch of other ways too, as he had a ton of new questions for his Guide. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf4 [Did he have some kind of status screen where he could see his stats, skills and titles?]}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  What were classes? Okay, he had a pretty good idea what classes probably were, but he wanted confirmation. How did he get a class? How did he get more skills? Would any of his pre-System skills be recognized by the System? How could he learn more about using his mana? Did the existence of mana imply the existence of magic? There was just a lot he didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t know. Yet.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Marcus resumed his deep breathing, this time to calm his excitement instead of the mana raging through him. It seemed increasingly like the arrival of the System in their universe was about to dump them into a reality that bore a strong resemblance to the video and tabletop roleplaying games he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d always loved. That had a lot of troubling implications when he thought about it. Those kinds of game worlds were rarely safe or tranquil. Is that what the System meant by promoting competition between organisms? And rewarding them by letting them see their improvement in the things they did and even granting titles when they do something truly impressive? }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It would definitely light a fire under some to explore everything the system had to offer and improve themselves. He knew that his people, his friends, his daughter, his brother and sister-in-law and their family, would probably be fine. All of them were gamers of one sort or another and had the innate gamer addiction to the dopamine hits from watching numbers go up. Hell they probably wouldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t just be fine, they\u8217\'92d probably thrive. Other folks though? There would be a lot of people who would struggle in such a radically changed world. In fact, he\u8217\'92d wager that human society as it was died the day the System came to Earth.}
